{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527240"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:30:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:30:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14195"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583969"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:33:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:33:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14195"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14195"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.1,0.01,0.87,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6881"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102745"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6881"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14195"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85228"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"928"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11356"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"},{"type":"tags","id":"12734"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29683"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102745"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her family for a routine health check. She identifies as Aboriginal. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. You are a non-Indigenous doctor who has recently started working in this community.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate approach to communicate effectively with this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Use medical jargon to demonstrate your expertise","Inquire about her connection to country and traditional healing practices","Focus solely on her individual health needs without involving family members","Introduce yourself, explain your role, and ask how she would like to be addressed","Ask if she prefers to be called by her first name or surname"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen communicating with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander patients, it\u0027s crucial to approach the interaction with cultural competence and respect. The most appropriate first step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eintroduce yourself, explain your role, and ask how she would like to be addressed\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach demonstrates respect, allows the patient to feel comfortable, and sets the tone for a positive interaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsking if she prefers to be called by her first name or surname\u003C/strong\u003E is not incorrect, but it\u0027s not as comprehensive as the correct option. It\u0027s better to give the patient more control over how they wish to be addressed, which may include a preferred name or title that isn\u0027t necessarily their first or last name.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUsing medical jargon to demonstrate your expertise\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate and can create barriers to effective communication. It\u0027s important to use clear, understandable language with all patients, regardless of their background, and to check understanding throughout the consultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInquiring about her connection to country and traditional healing practices\u003C/strong\u003E can be appropriate in some contexts, but it shouldn\u0027t be the first approach. This could be perceived as stereotyping if not done sensitively and at an appropriate time in the consultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFocusing solely on her individual health needs without involving family members\u003C/strong\u003E fails to recognise the importance of family and community in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander cultures. While respecting patient privacy, it\u0027s often beneficial to include family in health discussions if the patient wishes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEffective communication with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander patients involves building trust, showing respect, and being aware of cultural sensitivities. This includes using appropriate language, avoiding stereotypes or assumptions, actively listening, and allowing time for responses. It\u0027s also important to recognise the significance of family and community in health decisions. By starting the interaction with a respectful introduction and giving the patient control over how they wish to be addressed, you set the foundation for a positive and culturally competent healthcare experience.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Culturally competent communication with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander patients involves using respectful language and avoiding stereotypes or assumptions.","Building trust and rapport is essential when communicating with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander patients, which includes active listening and allowing time for responses.","Recognising the importance of family and community in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander cultures is crucial for effective healthcare communication."],"references":["New South Wales Ministry of Health. (2019, July 1). Communicating positively: A guide to appropriate Aboriginal terminology (GL2019_008). Centre for Aboriginal Health. https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/policies/gl/2019/pdf/GL2019_008.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85228"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14195"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85228"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-15T12:30:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-15T12:31:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6881"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102745"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduatin